05797nam a22007575i 9780774832915DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748329157 a10.59962/97807748329152doi  a(DE-B1597)661506  a(OCoLC)1394872808  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aGF657 .M35bE47 2018 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a304.20951822300aEmpire and Environment in the Making of Manchuria /ced. by Norman Smith. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (316 p.) :b22 photographs, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Chinese Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tManchuria: History and Environment -- tRival Empires on the Hunt for Sable and People in Seventeenth-Century Manchuria -- tInclement Weather and Human Error: Regular Irregularities in the Manchurian Tribute System during the Qing Dynasty -- tProducing Full-Fat Controversy: The Politicization of Dairy Production in Post-Colonial North Manchuria, 1924–30 -- t“Hibernate No More!”: Winter, Health, and the Great Outdoors -- tConstructing a Rural Utopia: Propaganda Images of Japanese Settlers in Northern Manchuria, 1936–43 -- tThe Garden of Grand Vision: Slums, Deviance, and Control in Manchukuo, 1940–41 -- tSalvaging Memories: Former Japanese Colonists in Manchuria and the Shimoina Project, 2001–12 -- tExile to Manchuria: Stories in the Qing and the PRC -- t“War against the Earth”: Military Farming in Communist Manchuria, 1949–75 -- tGlossary -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the seventeenth century, Chinese, Japanese, Manchu, Russian, and other imperial forces have defied Manchuria’s unrelenting summers and unforgiving winters to fight for sovereignty over the natural resources of Northeast Asia. Until now, historians have focused on rivalries between the region’s imperial invaders. Empire and Environment in the Making of Manchuria examines the interplay of climate and competing economic and political interests in the region’s vibrant – and violent – cultural narrative. In this unique and compelling analysis of Manchuria’s environmental history, contributors demonstrate how geography shaped the region’s past. Families that settled this borderland reaped its riches while at the mercy of an unforgiving and hotly contested landscape. As China’s strength as a world leader continues to grow, this volume invites exploration of the indelible links between empire and environment – and shows how the geopolitical future of this global economic powerhouse is rooted in its past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEcology. 0aGeopoliticszChinazManchuriaxCongressesxHistory. 0aGéographie humainexHistoirexChine. 0aHuman ecologyzChinazManchuriaxHistoryvCongresses. 0aHuman geographyxHistoryxChinaxManchuria. 0aHuman geographyzChinazManchuriaxHistoryvCongresses. 0aHuman geographyzChinazManchuriaxHistory. 0aHuman geography. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aBello, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiasson, Blaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCulver, Annika A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Loretta E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLary, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNing, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Norman, econtribu